'''Ole Kirk Christiansen''' (7 April 1891 &ndash; 11 March 1958) was the founder of the [[Denmark|Danish]] [[construction toy]] company [[The Lego Group]]. 

Christiansen was born in [[:da:Filskov|Filskov, South Jutland]], Denmark, the 10th son of an impoverished family in [[Jutland]]. {{cn|date=September 2017}} He trained as a [[carpenter]] and started making wooden toys in 1932 to make a living after having lost his job during the [[Great Depression]]. Soon after, his wife Kirstine died, leaving him to raise his four sons. Christiansen was inspired to construct a small wooden duck toy for his children. He never remarried. He soon learned his sons loved the new toy and decided to put the ducks into production, using the leftover wood from his old business.{{cn|date=September 2017}}

In 1942, a fire broke out at the factory, forcing them to rebuild. Initially, he made miniature versions of the houses and furniture as he worked on as a carpenter, but in 1947 moved to using plastics, which were originally small plastic bears and rattles. By 1949 he had produced over 200 plastic and wooden toys.{{cn|date=September 2017}}

Ole wanted a name for the group. In 1934 he launched a competition to name the company. The prize was a bottle of his own homemade wine. He won it himself.{{Failed verification|date=May 2018|reason=These sentences were probably lifted from some official Lego book rather than citing it, I've heard it before but its not in these citations}} Lego is a shortened form of the Danish words ''leg godt'', meaning "play well", and the company grew to become The Lego Group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inventors.about.com/library/inventors/bllego.htm|title=Timeline: Lego Group|publisher=Inventors.about.com|author=Mary Bellis|date=1 May 1954|accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref> 

On 11 March 1958, Christiansen died from a heart attack at the age of 66,{{cn|date=May 2018}} and his third son [[Godtfred Kirk Christiansen|Godtfred]] promptly took over the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/invent/iow/christiansen.html|title=Inventor of the Week: Ole Kirk Christiansen|publisher=Lemelson-MIT Program|date=December 2004|archivedate=27 May 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527123958/http://web.mit.edu/invent/iow/christiansen.html |accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>

